 First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":12,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Nicholas Zouche was born about 1278, in Wokingham, Berkshire, England. He married Elizabeth Zouche before 20 January 1288, in England. He died on 12 July 1311, in Frome, Somerset, England, at the age of 34."},"et":{"about 1278–12 July 1311":"umbes 1278–12. juuli 1311","1308–1360":"1308–1360","1274–1350":"1274–1350","1315–1382":"1315–1382","1332–1394":"1332–1394","1278–1311":"1278–1311","1274":"1274","before 20 January 1288":"enne 20. jaanuari 1288","1394":"1394","1350":"1350","12 July 1311":"12. juuli 1311","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1311":"1311","1278":"1278","1332":"1332","about 1278":"umbes 1278